Main Street, west side, south of Northern Boulevard to Thirtyninth Ave. St. George's Protestant Episcopal Church is in the background on Thirty-ninth Ave. TThe brick front structure next to the one bearing the sign plate W. 727327f-a.text:
Main St., (old Nos. 11,13,l5) west side, south of Northern Boulevard. Caleb W. Smith, left foreground, lived here in 1870. He operated a candy store. Geo Barron occupied the center house. He was a friend of Smith's. Mr. Barron kept a clothing store here. He died in this small house in 1926. Woolworth store occupies
the site in 1922.
1922

727569f-c.text:
Northern Boulevard, south side, east of Main St., showing in a set of 4 views the rear and side of the Quaker Meeting house, erected in 1694. The lock on the inside is encased in an oak block about 8'x14"l 1V2" and is fastened by hand made screws. It is the original lock. The wood burning stoves, found still in service here, were imported from England over two hundred years Sgo. The heat is distributed by pipes extending along the ceiling.
July 1925.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection

727330f-a.text:
Main Street (foreground), at the S.E. corner of Northern Boulevard, showing the Fountain House. In 183O Benj. P. Lowerre, later Charles P. Lowerre, and in 1873 the C.P. Lowerre Estate owned this tavern. Eucene L. Armbruster states that Jacob F. Haubeil was long the owner of this tavern. He lived at 136 Broadway and never lived in the Fountain House. Bis pater operated, built, and owned the Washington Hotel in 1855. The building in this view does not appear in the Queens Atlas of
1926.
1922.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

727570f-b.text:
orthern Boulevard, south side, east of Main St., showing in a set of three views the Quaker Meeting House of Flushing. The land upon which this building was erected;from 1694-57was puchased in 1692 for the sum of f 40. On May 30, 1696 their first annual meeting was held here. This building was shingled plastered, and repaired in 1704. The Quaker records state1 A new building was erected in 1719 near the old one and was 65'x42' in size. This refers probably to an addition. In 1763, the gallery was taken out and a floor was laid, making it a two story structure. The British used the structure as a barrack, hospital, prison, and bay magazine; being restored to the original owner in 1783. The Orthodox Quakers built a meeting house east of the old (Hicksite), meeting house in the 183O's. The picket fence surrounding this building as removed in 1911, and the
Orthodox Meeting House in 1909
1922
View 2: March 1924.
View 3: July 1925.
